\f2\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 unknown_pack
\f0\fs24 \
\ls15\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 non_pack_branding
\f0\fs24 \
\ls15\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 non_cigarette_rectangular_object
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 Without those hard negatives, your detector will over-fire on labels, posters, and shelf tags.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 H. Hybrid model architecture\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 The recommended architecture is:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \strokec2 Image QA \uc0\u8594  Pack Detector \u8594  Crop Processor \u8594  OCR + Visual Retrieval + Hierarchical Classifier \u8594  VLM Arbitrator for hard cases \u8594  Fusion Engine \u8594  Confidence Gate \u8594  Auto-approve or Human Review
\f0\fs24 \strokec2 \
This follows two strong lines of evidence:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls16\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 shelf-recognition research showing value in 
\f1\b product-agnostic detection + similarity search on cropped items
\f0\b0  ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://arxiv.org/abs/1810.01733"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 arXiv}})\
\ls16\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 fine-grained grocery research showing that 
\f1\b image + OCR text
\f0\b0  together improve recognition, especially with subtle SKU differences and limited data ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00138-024-01549-9"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Springer}})\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Detector choice\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 RF-DETR is a valid detector choice because its official docs and repository center it around custom training/fine-tuning, and the core package and Apache-designated weights are Apache 2.0 licensed. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://roboflow.github.io/rf-detr/learn/train/?utm_source=chatgpt.com"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 roboflow.github.io}})\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 Critical design choice\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Train the first detector as 
\f1\b class-agnostic
\f0\b0  or 
\f1\b mother-brand-light
\f0\b0 , not full flat-SKU detection.\uc0\u8232 Why:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls17\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 box localization and SKU distinction are different problems\
\ls17\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 flat SKU detection creates class explosion too early\
\ls17\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 annotation cost rises sharply\
\ls17\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 similar SKUs will confuse the detector when text details are tiny\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 I. Image QA gating and crop generation\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 The detector should output:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls18\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 bounding box\
\ls18\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 objectness\
\ls18\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 visible area estimate\
\ls18\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 crop margin\
\ls18\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 optional orientation estimate\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 After detection, each crop should go through:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls19\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 perspective correction if possible\
\ls19\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 rotation normalization\
\ls19\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 crop padding\
\ls19\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 optional super-resolution only for low-res crops that still pass minimum size thresholds\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 Do not apply expensive enhancement blindly. Enhancement should be conditional and measurable.\
Recommended crop-level derived fields:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls20\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 crop_width
\f0\fs24 \
\ls20\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 crop_height
\f0\fs24 \
\ls20\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 crop_visible_fraction
\f0\fs24 \
\ls20\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 crop_rotation_class
\f0\fs24 \
\ls20\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 crop_ocr_legibility_score
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 J. Job orchestration and system flow\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 This system is inherently asynchronous. Use a proper queue, not synchronous request chaining. Cloud Tasks is explicitly designed for large numbers of distributed tasks and asynchronous work outside the user request path; Google also warns it is not for interactive situations where a user is waiting on the result. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://docs.cloud.google.com/tasks/docs"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Google Cloud Documentation}})\
Recommended execution flow:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls21\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 API receives batch job\
\ls21\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Persist job + image records\
\ls21\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Enqueue per-image task\
\ls21\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Detector service processes image\
\ls21\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Enqueue per-crop recognition tasks\
\ls21\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	6	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Fusion service assembles image result\
\ls21\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	7	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Outlet aggregator computes final outlet result\
\ls21\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	8	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Export worker writes XLSX/CSV\
\ls21\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	9	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 UI shows progress and review queue\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 This decoupling is not optional if you want stable retries, partial recovery, and scalable throughput.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 K. Knowledge base and retrieval subsystem\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 For crop recognition, build a 
\f1\b retrieval layer
\f0\b0  against the canonical SKU catalog.\
Use:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls22\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 multimodal or image embeddings for crop-to-catalog similarity\
\ls22\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 OCR tokens as secondary ranking signals\
\ls22\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 brand-family constraints\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 Google\'92s multimodal embeddings docs explicitly position the model for image classification and retail-like use cases, where product images and text can be embedded for downstream search/classification tasks. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://docs.cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/generative-ai/docs/embeddings/get-multimodal-embeddings"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Google Cloud Documentation}})\
Storage options:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls23\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 pgvector
\f0\b0  if you want simple operational integration with Postgres; Supabase documents pgvector as a Postgres extension for storing embeddings and vector similarity search. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://supabase.com/docs/guides/database/extensions/pgvector"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Supabase}})\
\ls23\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 FAISS
\f0\b0  if you want a high-performance local/vector-service index; FAISS is purpose-built for efficient dense-vector similarity search and clustering. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://faiss.ai/index.html?utm_source=chatgpt.com"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Faiss}})\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 My recommendation:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls24\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 start with 
\f1\b Postgres + pgvector
\f0\b0 \
\ls24\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 move to FAISS only if catalog size or query latency forces it\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 L. Language and OCR subsystem\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 OCR should be treated as a 
\f1\b primary model signal
\f0\b0 , not a nice-to-have.\
Why:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls25\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 many cigarette SKUs differ by tiny words, numerals, or flavor/strength text\
\ls25\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 the detector may localize correctly while image-only classifiers still confuse subtle variants\
\ls25\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 multimodal grocery research shows image + OCR text beats unimodal models in fine-grained recognition, especially when samples are limited. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00138-024-01549-9"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Springer}})\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 PaddleOCR is a good practical baseline because the official project positions it as a lightweight OCR toolkit supporting 
\f1\b 100+ languages
\f0\b0 . ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/PADDLEPADDLE/PADDLEOCR"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 GitHub}})\
OCR pipeline spec:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls26\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 run OCR on normalized crop\
\ls26\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 normalize script mix and casing\
\ls26\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 remove generic warning/legal stopwords\
\ls26\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 fuzzy-match against SKU alias table\
\ls26\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 emit token evidence with confidence\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 Store OCR evidence, not just the final resolved text.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 M. Model training plan\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 M1. Detector\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Train RF-DETR first on:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls27\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 cigarette_pack
\f0\fs24 \
\ls27\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 non_pack_branding
\f0\fs24 \
\ls27\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 price_label
\f0\fs24 \
\ls27\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 other_rectangular_object
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 Then optionally fine-tune a second version with 
\f2\fs26 \strokec2 mother_brand
\f0\fs24 \strokec2  labels. RF-DETR\'92s training docs support custom training through the Python package or managed cloud flow. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://roboflow.github.io/rf-detr/learn/train/?utm_source=chatgpt.com"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 roboflow.github.io}})\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 M2. Crop recognizer\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Use a two-track recognizer:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls28\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 retrieval/embedding model
\f0\b0  for top-k nearest SKU candidates\
\ls28\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 hierarchical classifier
\f0\b0 :\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls28\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 head A: mother brand\
\ls28\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 head B: SKU within predicted family\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 This is stronger than a single flat 100-class SKU classifier.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 M3. VLM arbitrator\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Use Gemini only for 
\f1\b hard cases
\f0\b0 , not as the first-line detector. Vertex supports supervised fine-tuning for Gemini, including image tuning. The tuning API recommends 
\f1\b at least 100 to 500 examples
\f0\b0  for best results, and validation datasets can contain up to 
\f1\b 256 examples
\f0\b0 . ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://docs.cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/generative-ai/docs/model-reference/tuning"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Google Cloud Documentation}})\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 M4. Image tuning constraints\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Vertex image tuning currently documents:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls29\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 max 
\f1\b 30 images per example
\f0\b0 \
\ls29\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 max 
\f1\b 20 MB per image
\f0\b0 \
\ls29\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 media resolution control affecting token usage. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://docs.cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/generative-ai/docs/models/tune_gemini/image_tune"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Google Cloud Documentation}})\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 So for this system, tune Gemini on 
\f1\b hard cropped cases
\f0\b0  and 
\f1\b small grouped crop panels
\f0\b0 , not raw huge shelf images whenever possible.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

